{\textgreater} Thus , laterally transported macroalgal drift nearshore kelp forests may play a more important role in the flux of organic carbon to deep-sea environments than previously recognised. This may partially explain the descrepancy between carbon flux and carbon demand of the benthos recently reported for the continental margin deep-sea habitats. Carbon flux estimates from particle traps do not account for laterally advected macroalagal drift, which may be a quantitatively important process in coastal habitats.},
