Danger point showed low recruitment between November 1992 and November 1993, followed by significantly higher but variable densities for he rest of the study period. This indicates long-term or stochastic patterns. The episodic nature of kelp recruitment is well documented. E. Maxima appears to be adapted to disturbance because of the high spore output, and the gametophytes, and juvenile sporophytes grow rapidly. 

The authors concluded that density of E. maxima at this site seems to be determined by grazing and availability of primary space on the substratum. In this case, grazers seem to have a controlling effect on the density of the young kelp sporophytes at Danger Point. A past study by Fricke 1979 showed that urchin removal lead to increased kelp recruitment. However, in another study by Day (1998) found that, in the same area, urchin removals had negligible effect on algae, including kelp sporelings. In this study, high recruitment was present at both sites, and most of the juveniles were located in Refugio provided by kelp holdfasts. 

The present study showed that, at Danger Point, the kelp bed recovered from harvesting in about two years, in terms of biomass and kelp density. Understorey communities were essentially unchanged two years after harvesting, and showed no visual signs of change at any stage.

